  <title>A federal tax credit worth up to $2,000 most homeowners don't claim</title>
</head>
<body style="margin:0;padding:0;background-color:#ffffff;font-family:-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,'Segoe UI',Roboto,Helvetica,Arial,sans-serif;color:#27272a;">
  <div style="max-width:600px;margin:0 auto;padding:32px 20px;">

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      A week ago you calculated a {{ home.tonnage }}-ton system for your {{ home.sqft | comma }} sqft {{ location.city }} home. Today's email is about turning that into actual money off, via a federal tax credit most homeowners don't know to ask for.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">Where this credit comes from</h2>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      In 2022, Congress passed the <strong>Inflation Reduction Act</strong> (IRA) &mdash; a law that included a long list of incentives for energy-efficient home upgrades. <strong>Section 25C</strong> of the IRA covers HVAC. Specifically:
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;background-color:#fff7ed;border-left:3px solid #FF6B2B;padding:12px 16px;">
      If you install a qualifying heat pump in 2026, you get <strong>30% of project cost back as a federal tax credit, capped at $2,000</strong>.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;"><strong>A few important details:</strong></p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">This is a <strong>tax credit</strong>, not a tax deduction. Big difference. A <em>deduction</em> lowers the income you pay tax on (so a $2,000 deduction at a 24% tax rate saves you $480). A <em>credit</em> lowers your tax bill directly, dollar for dollar &mdash; $2,000 credit = $2,000 less owed to the IRS, or $2,000 more in your refund.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;">The credit applies <strong>only to heat pumps</strong> &mdash; not to traditional central air conditioners or gas furnaces. (Those qualify for separate, smaller credits under the same law.) If you weren't already considering a heat pump, this credit might tip the math.</li>
      <li>The total annual cap on all 25C improvements (heat pumps, water heaters, insulation, windows, etc.) is $3,200, with the $2,000 heat-pump cap nested inside it.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">Quick refresher on what a heat pump is</h2>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      A <strong>heat pump</strong> is a single piece of HVAC equipment that handles both heating and cooling. Mechanically it works the same way as an air conditioner &mdash; moving heat from one place to another &mdash; but it can run in either direction. In summer it pulls heat out of your home (cooling). In winter it pulls heat from outside air (yes, even cold outside air still has heat in it) and brings that heat indoors. One outdoor unit, no separate furnace, no fuel burning. Modern ones work down to about -10&deg;F without any backup heat needed.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">Three flavors all qualify for 25C:</p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 24px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong>Ducted air-source heat pump</strong> &mdash; uses your existing ductwork, like a traditional central AC. Most common for whole-home installs.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:8px;"><strong>Ductless mini-split</strong> &mdash; small wall-mounted indoor units that don't need ducts. Common for additions or homes that never had ductwork.</li>
      <li><strong>Geothermal heat pump</strong> &mdash; pulls heat from the ground rather than the air. More expensive up front; covered under a different (larger) IRA section, but the same idea.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">The plain-English rules for claiming the 25C credit</h2>

    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:20px 0 8px 0;">1. The equipment has to meet efficiency thresholds.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      Specifically, for 2026 installs, the IRS requires equipment that meets the <strong>CEE highest tier</strong> (excluding any "advanced" tier). <strong>CEE</strong> stands for Consortium for Energy Efficiency &mdash; an industry nonprofit that publishes efficiency tiers, which the IRS adopted as the goalposts for who qualifies. In practice: high-efficiency equipment, but not the absolute top of the line. Your contractor should know which models qualify; if they can't tell you, that's a red flag.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      <strong>The numbers your contractor will reference (here's what they all mean):</strong>
    </p>
    <ul style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px 24px;padding:0;">
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>SEER2</strong> = Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio (cooling). It's a measure of how much cooling you get per unit of electricity, averaged across a typical cooling season. Higher = more efficient. As benchmarks: SEER2 13-14 is budget; 16-18 is mid-range; 20+ is high-efficiency.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>HSPF2</strong> = Heating Seasonal Performance Factor. Same idea, but for heating. Higher = more heat per unit of electricity. Benchmarks: 7 is budget; 8-9 is solid; 9+ is high-efficiency, and it's roughly the threshold the 25C credit requires for qualifying heat pumps.</li>
      <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong>EER2</strong> = Energy Efficiency Ratio at peak conditions (the hottest hour of the hottest day). Higher = the system holds up under stress, not just on average days.</li>
      <li><strong>Why "2"?</strong> SEER2 / HSPF2 / EER2 are the same metrics measured under a newer (post-2023) test standard. Older SEER / HSPF numbers (without the 2) are not directly comparable &mdash; for rough conversion, an old "16 SEER" rating &asymp; "15 SEER2" today.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:20px 0 8px 0;">2. You need a manufacturer's certification statement.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      Every qualifying model has a <strong>manufacturer's certification statement</strong> &mdash; a one-page PDF from the manufacturer that explicitly says "this specific model meets the 25C efficiency thresholds for tax year 2026." That's the document you (or your tax preparer) reference when filing.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      <strong>Ask the contractor for this PDF before you sign the contract</strong>, not after. A reputable contractor can produce it in five minutes &mdash; they get it routinely from the manufacturer or distributor. A contractor who can't or won't is either (a) not familiar with 25C, or (b) selling you a model that doesn't qualify and hoping you won't notice. Either way, that's the contractor you don't hire.
    </p>

    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:20px 0 8px 0;">3. You file IRS Form 5695 with your federal tax return.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      The credit is claimed on <strong>Form 5695, line 22a</strong>. It's one number, on one line. The hard part is gathering the paperwork (the manufacturer's certification statement, the contractor's itemized invoice). The actual filing is the easiest part.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      If you use TurboTax or H&amp;R Block, look for the "Energy-Saving Home Improvements" section &mdash; they'll prompt you for everything. If you use a CPA, hand them the certification statement and the invoice; they'll know exactly what to do.
    </p>

    <h3 style="font-size:16px;color:#18181b;margin:20px 0 8px 0;">4. The credit stacks with state and utility rebates.</h3>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 24px 0;">
      This part matters: the federal $2,000 doesn't get reduced by anything you receive at the state or utility level. So if your utility offers a $500 rebate AND your state offers a $1,500 rebate, you can stack them: $500 (utility) + $1,500 (state) + up to $2,000 (federal) = $4,000 off the install.
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">For your situation specifically</h2>

    {% if location.climate_region == "Cold" %}
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      You're in a cold climate (zone {{ location.iecc_zone }}, design heating temperature around {{ location.design_temp_low }}&deg;F), where the heat pump credit is most valuable. Modern cold-climate heat pumps clear the HSPF2 9 threshold without needing exotic equipment. If a contractor pushes back with "heat pumps don't work well in cold weather" &mdash; that hasn't been true for a decade. Ask specifically: "Do you install cold-climate heat pumps? Which models?" Their answer reveals whether they're current.
    </p>
    {% endif %}

    {% if location.climate_region == "Hot" %}
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      You're in a hot climate, where almost any modern heat pump clears the SEER2 and EER2 thresholds. The bigger question is whether the contractor recommends a heat pump at all, or defaults to a traditional central AC + gas furnace combo. The traditional combo is cheaper up front, but central AC alone <em>doesn't</em> qualify for the $2,000 credit &mdash; only heat pumps do. If you're open to a heat pump, push for that option specifically.
    </p>
    {% endif %}

    {% if location.climate_region == "Warm" or location.climate_region == "Mixed" or location.climate_region == "Cool" %}
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      A heat pump is a no-brainer for your zone (IECC {{ location.iecc_zone }}), and the SEER2 / HSPF2 thresholds are easy to meet. The watch-out: some contractors quote a qualifying outdoor unit but pair it with an older indoor coil, dropping the system's overall rating below the threshold and voiding the credit. Insist on AHRI-matched components (see Day 3, item 2) &mdash; and verify the certification statement is for the matched pair, not the outdoor unit by itself.
    </p>
    {% endif %}

    {% if home.tonnage <= 2 %}
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      Your {{ home.tonnage }}-ton load is on the smaller side, which means ductless mini-splits are very competitive options for you. Mini-splits qualify for the same $2,000 cap as ducted heat pumps, with their own (slightly higher) efficiency thresholds. Worth comparing both ducted and mini-split bids if your home doesn't already have ductwork.
    </p>
    {% endif %}

    {% if home.tonnage > 5 %}
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      Your {{ home.tonnage }}-ton load is on the larger end. Qualifying heat pumps exist at this size, but the market thins out &mdash; your contractor may propose splitting your home into two systems (two outdoor units, each handling part of the home). Each separate heat pump can qualify independently for the $2,000 credit if installed in different tax years. Worth asking about.
    </p>
    {% endif %}

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">The state-level rebate stack</h2>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      {{ location.state }} runs its own rebate programs alongside the federal credit. The U.S. Department of Energy rolled out two big programs in 2024 &mdash; <strong>HEEHRA</strong> (the High-Efficiency Electric Home Rebate Act, which gives upfront rebates rather than tax credits) and <strong>HOMES</strong> (the HOMES Rebate Program, which gives rebates based on actual energy savings). Both are funded by the IRA and administered state-by-state, so the launch date varies. Some states are live; others aren't yet.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;">
      For up-to-date {{ location.state }} programs, check <strong>DSIRE</strong> &mdash; the Database of State Incentives for Renewables &amp; Efficiency, run by NC State University. DSIRE is the canonical, free, public list of every federal/state/utility incentive in the U.S.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 24px 0;">
      Direct link for {{ location.state }}: <a href="{{ rebate_lookup_url }}" style="color:#FF6B2B;text-decoration:underline;">{{ rebate_lookup_url }}</a>
    </p>

    <h2 style="font-size:17px;color:#18181b;margin:32px 0 12px 0;">One specific contractor competence test</h2>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 12px 0;">
      When you're talking to contractors, this question separates the ones who file 25C regularly from the ones who don't:
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;font-style:italic;border-left:3px solid #e4e4e7;padding-left:16px;color:#3f3f46;">
      "Is this equipment 25C-eligible, and will you provide the manufacturer's certification statement?"
    </p>
    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 28px 0;">
      A contractor who says "yes, here's the certification &mdash; and we can walk you through Form 5695" files this credit regularly. A contractor who hesitates, dodges, or says "talk to your CPA" hasn't done it before &mdash; and you'd be the guinea pig. Note who answers cleanly. That's almost always the contractor you want.
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 28px 0;">
      <a href="{{ cta_url }}" style="color:#FF6B2B;font-weight:600;text-decoration:underline;">Angi can connect you with pros experienced filing 25C &rarr;</a>
    </p>

    <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 4px 0;">&mdash; NailTheQuote</p>
    <p style="font-size:14px;line-height:1.65;margin:0 0 16px 0;color:#71717a;font-style:italic;">
      P.S. The $2,000 cap resets every year. So if you're staging a multi-system project &mdash; say, a heat pump this year, a heat-pump water heater next year &mdash; you can claim 25C in both tax years.
    </p>

